{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Qmua1sjCF3YFP2jb8yKkuC","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 8-7: Rust OTLP Instrumentation\n     2→\n     3→Status: review\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer instrumenting a Rust project,\n    10→I want codeharness to add OpenTelemetry crates and provide setup guidance,\n    11→so that I can quickly enable observability.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **AC1:** Given a Rust project, when `instrumentProject()` runs, then `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber` is executed and `packages_installed` returns `true` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **AC2:** Given OTLP instrumentation succeeds on a Rust project, when state is updated, then `configureOtlpEnvVars()` writes `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` and `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` to `.env.codeharness` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **AC3:** Given a Rust project, when `configureAgent()` is called, then it skips with info message (no standard Rust agent SDK yet) and does NOT install any packages or set `agent_sdk` in state <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **AC4:** Given `templates/otlp/rust.md` exists, when read, then it contains: packages to add (`cargo add` command), `tracing_subscriber` setup code snippet, `#[tracing::instrument]` usage, environment variables (`OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`, `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME`), and verification steps <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **AC5:** Given `installRustOtlp()` is called and `cargo add` fails, then it returns `{ status: 'failed', packages_installed: false }` with an error message <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **AC6:** Given a Rust project, when `instrumentProject()` runs in non-json mode, then it prints an info message about Rust OTLP packages being installed <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **AC7:** Given all changes, when `npm test` runs, then all existing tests pass with zero regressions and new Rust OTLP tests pass <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    22→8. **AC8:** Given `codeharness init` runs on a Rust project, when the OTLP instrumentation phase executes, then it runs `cargo add` for the OTLP crates (not just env vars) <!-- verification: integration-required -->\n    23→\n    24→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    25→\n    26→- [x] Task 1: Add `RUST_OTLP_PACKAGES` constant and `installRustOtlp()` function to `src/lib/otlp.ts` (AC: #1, #5)\n    27→  - [x]1.1 Add `const RUST_OTLP_PACKAGES = ['opentelemetry', 'opentelemetry-otlp', 'tracing-opentelemetry', 'tracing-subscriber'];` after `PYTHON_OTLP_PACKAGES`\n    28→  - [x]1.2 Create `installRustOtlp(projectDir: string): OtlpResult` following `installNodeOtlp()` pattern\n    29→  - [x]1.3 Run `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber` via `execFileSync`\n    30→  - [x]1.4 Return `{ status: 'configured', packages_installed: true, ... }` on success\n    31→  - [x]1.5 Return `{ status: 'failed', packages_installed: false, error: '...' }` on failure with truncated error message\n    32→- [x] Task 2: Update `instrumentProject()` Rust branch to call `installRustOtlp()` (AC: #1, #6)\n    33→  - [x]2.1 Replace the current placeholder Rust branch (L318-329) with actual `installRustOtlp()` call\n    34→  - [x]2.2 On success, print `ok('OTLP: Rust packages installed')` in non-json mode\n    35→  - [x]2.3 On failure, the existing error handling path covers it (L369-371)\n    36→- [x] Task 3: Add `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` to `.env.codeharness` for Rust (AC: #2)\n    37→  - [x]3.1 In `configureOtlpEnvVars()`, after calling `ensureServiceNameEnvVar()`, add Rust-specific logic to also write `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` to `.env.codeharness` (Rust reads env vars directly, unlike Node.js `--require` or Python wrapper)\n    38→  - [x]3.2 Use same file append/update pattern as `ensureServiceNameEnvVar()`\n    39→- [x] Task 4: Add Rust case to `configureAgent()` — skip with info (AC: #3)\n    40→  - [x]4.1 Add `else if (stack === 'rust')` branch after the Python branch (L227)\n    41→  - [x]4.2 Log info message: `info('Rust agent SDK not yet supported — skipping agent configuration')`\n    42→  - [x]4.3 Return early — do NOT set `agent_sdk` in state (no Rust agent SDK exists)\n    43→- [x] Task 5: Create `templates/otlp/rust.md` (AC: #4)\n    44→  - [x]5.1 Follow pattern of `templates/otlp/nodejs.md` (54 lines) and `templates/otlp/python.md` (52 lines)\n    45→  - [x]5.2 Section: Packages to Install — `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber`\n    46→  - [x]5.3 Section: Setup Code — `tracing_subscriber` initialization with OTLP exporter layer in `main.rs`\n    47→  - [x]5.4 Section: Function Instrumentation — `#[tracing::instrument]` attribute usage\n    48→  - [x]5.5 Section: Environment Variables — `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`, `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME`, etc.\n    49→  - [x]5.6 Section: Verification — How to confirm traces are being exported\n    50→- [x] Task 6: Add tests in `src/lib/__tests__/otlp.test.ts` (AC: #1, #2, #3, #5, #6, #7)\n    51→  - [x]6.1 Test: `installRustOtlp()` success — runs `cargo add` with correct packages\n    52→  - [x]6.2 Test: `installRustOtlp()` failure — returns failed status with error message\n    53→  - [x]6.3 Test: `instrumentProject()` with stack `'rust'` — calls `cargo add` and returns `packages_installed: true`\n    54→  - [x]6.4 Test: `instrumentProject()` Rust prints info message in non-json mode\n    55→  - [x]6.5 Test: `configureOtlpEnvVars()` with stack `'rust'` — writes `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` to `.env.codeharness`\n    56→  - [x]6.6 Test: `configureAgent()` with stack `'rust'` — skips without installing packages or setting agent_sdk\n    57→  - [x]6.7 Test: `installRustOtlp()` truncates long error messages\n    58→- [x] Task 7: Run full test suite — zero regressions (AC: #7)\n    59→\n    60→## Dev Notes\n    61→\n    62→### Current State of Rust in otlp.ts\n    63→\n    64→The `instrumentProject()` function already has a Rust branch (added in story 8-2 or earlier), but it's a **placeholder** that does NOT call `cargo add`:\n    65→\n    66→```typescript\n    67→} else if (stack === 'rust') {\n    68→    // Rust OTLP package installation is story 8-7.\n    69→    // For now, configure env vars and state hint only.\n    70→    result = {\n    71→      status: 'configured',\n    72→      packages_installed: false,  // <-- NOT INSTALLED\n    73→      start_script_patched: false,\n    74→      env_vars_configured: false,\n    75→    };\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→This story replaces that placeholder with a real `installRustOtlp()` call.\n    79→\n    80→### configureOtlpEnvVars Already Has Rust Branch\n    81→\n    82→The `configureOtlpEnvVars()` function already handles `stack === 'rust'` — it sets `rust_env_hint: 'OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT'` in state (added by story 8-2). However, it does NOT write `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` to `.env.codeharness`. This story adds that.\n    83→\n    84→The current `ensureServiceNameEnvVar()` only writes `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME`. For Rust projects, we also need `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` in `.env.codeharness` because Rust apps read env vars directly (unlike Node.js which uses `--require` flag or Python which uses `opentelemetry-instrument` wrapper).\n    85→\n    86→### configureAgent Does Not Have Rust Branch\n    87→\n    88→The `configureAgent()` function currently handles `'nodejs'` and `'python'` stacks. Any other stack (including `'rust'`) falls through and always sets `agent_sdk: 'traceloop'` in state — which is incorrect for Rust. This story adds an explicit Rust branch that skips and returns early.\n    89→\n    90→### Test Patterns\n    91→\n    92→Existing tests use:\n    93→- `vi.mock('node:child_process')` at module level\n    94→- Real temp directories via `mkdtempSync`\n    95→- `initState()` / `initStateWithOtlp()` helpers\n    96→- `mockExecFileSync` for verifying command invocations\n    97→\n    98→### File Line Budget\n    99→\n   100→`src/lib/otlp.ts` is currently 375 lines. Adding `RUST_OTLP_PACKAGES` (1 line), `installRustOtlp()` (~20 lines), Rust `configureAgent` branch (~4 lines), and env file writing (~10 lines) puts it at ~410 lines. This may exceed the 300-line limit from NFR1. If so, consider extracting `ensureServiceNameEnvVar` and the new endpoint helper into a small `otlp-env.ts` module, or accept the overage since `otlp.ts` was already at 330+ lines before this sprint.\n   101→\n   102→### Architecture Constraints\n   103→\n   104→- **No new npm dependencies**: Pure TypeScript, uses `execFileSync` from `node:child_process`\n   105→- **NFR5**: Follows existing `OtlpResult` return pattern\n   106→- **cargo add**: Adds all packages in one command (not one-by-one). If `cargo` is not available, `execFileSync` throws and the error is caught.\n   107→\n   108→### References\n   109→\n   110→- [Source: src/lib/otlp.ts — current OTLP module with Rust placeholder at L318-329]\n   111→- [Source: src/lib/otlp.ts#L207-227 — configureAgent() without Rust branch]\n   112→- [Source: src/lib/otlp.ts#L258-286 — configureOtlpEnvVars() with Rust state hint]\n   113→- [Source: src/lib/otlp.ts#L46-65 — installNodeOtlp() pattern to follow]\n   114→- [Source: src/lib/__tests__/otlp.test.ts — existing test patterns]\n   115→- [Source: templates/otlp/nodejs.md — 54-line Node.js guidance doc pattern]\n   116→- [Source: templates/otlp/python.md — 52-line Python guidance doc pattern]\n   117→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-rust-stack-support.md#Story8-7 — epic definition]\n   118→- [Source: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-rust-stack-support.md#Task4-5 — tech spec tasks]\n   119→\n   120→### Previous Story Intelligence (8-6)\n   121→\n   122→- 8-6 added Rust to `ProjectType`, `detectProjectType()`, `resolveDockerfileTemplate()`, and `buildVerifyImage()` in the verify module — no file overlap with this story.\n   123→- 8-6 confirmed 2998 tests pass, zero regressions.\n   124→- configureOtlpEnvVars Rust test already exists in otlp.test.ts (L242-253) — added by earlier story. New tests should not duplicate it.\n   125→\n   126→### Git Intelligence\n   127→\n   128→Recent commits: f33294b (8-6 verified), 79f3449 (8-5 verified), 4e805b9 (8-4 verified), ebaddac (8-3 verified), d6a76bf (8-2 verified).\n   129→This story touches `src/lib/otlp.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/otlp.test.ts`, and `templates/otlp/rust.md` — clean isolation from previous stories.\n   130→\n   131→### Do NOT Create\n   132→\n   133→- Do NOT modify `configureOtlpEnvVars()` Rust state hint — already done in 8-2\n   134→- Do NOT create Semgrep rules for Rust (that's story 8-9)\n   135→- Do NOT modify docs scaffolding (that's story 8-8)\n   136→- Do NOT modify stack detection (that's story 8-1, already done)\n   137→\n   138→### Project Structure Notes\n   139→\n   140→Files to create:\n   141→- `templates/otlp/rust.md` — LLM guidance doc for Rust OTLP instrumentation\n   142→\n   143→Files to modify:\n   144→- `src/lib/otlp.ts` — Add `RUST_OTLP_PACKAGES`, `installRustOtlp()`, update `instrumentProject()` Rust branch, add Rust to `configureAgent()`, add endpoint env var writing for Rust\n   145→- `src/lib/__tests__/otlp.test.ts` — Add Rust OTLP test cases\n   146→\n   147→Files for reference only (do NOT modify):\n   148→- `templates/otlp/nodejs.md` — Pattern for guidance doc\n   149→- `templates/otlp/python.md` — Pattern for guidance doc\n   150→\n   151→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   152→## Verification Requirements\n   153→\n   154→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/8-7-rust-otlp-instrumentation.proof.md`)\n   155→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified